{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558388/1937112401/0305.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nPartly cloudy Wednesday night\nand Thursday with slowly rising\ntemperature*.\nGOOD AFTERNOON\nFor the intelligence service in\nthe next war, how about using\njobless vaudeville hams to locate\nthe enemy's tank towns?\nLargest Daily Circulation of Any Newspaper in North Carolina in Proportion to Population\nVOL. 56\u2014No. 281\nHENDERSONVILLE, N. C., WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 24, 1937\nSINGLE COPIES, FIVE CENTS\n\\lj\nAY PAST PICKETS\n\n*JP\nTo Assert Self\nWHEELER SEES\n'REACTIONARY'\nSWING LIKELY\nUrges New Deal to Show\nIt Would Not Wreck\nBusiness\nFISH CHARGES LOSS\nDUE TO POLICIES\nWASHINGTON. Nov. j:. P).\nSenator Burton K. Wheeler today\ncalled upon the administration to\n\"raassurv the peopie that it is not\nseeking to ilntrtA' bus:ne-*.'\nHe a<lviji'd such lea ssurancc\nlest the public fears cause \"a\nswing of the pendulum to the re\nactionaries.\"\nWheeler said that a business\nrecession could not be blamed on\nany one thing but thai he believ\ned that with congress in a more\nindependent mood than previous\nly the administration could re\nstore confidence by a general\nprogram intended to re-assure the\ncountry.\nFISH BLAMES POLICY\nFOR LOSS IN V ALUES\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 21. (CPi.\n\u2014President Roosevelt's policies\nwere blamed by Representative\nHamilton Fish. Jr., R.. N. Y in\nthe hous\u00ab yesterday for a S.'IO.\n000.000.000 loss in security\nvalues on stock exchanges during\nthe past two months.\nFish's charge against his most\ndistinguished constituent brought\na counter blast from Repress :;ta\ntivc Adolph Sabath. L>., Ill d\u00ab*nit\nof the house, that the current\nbusiness recession resulted frr\u00bbm\na \"strike engineered by Wall\nStreet and the bankers.\"\nFish retorted that administra\ntion policies might have caused\nanother $30.000.000.000 shrink\nage on unlisted securities which\nhe ttaid would mean \"further un\nemployment of American labor.\"\n\"I deny thi.N is a Roosevelt de\npression.\" Sabbath heatedly r\u00bb\u00ab\nplied. *I't is a Wall Street con\nspiracy whose aim is to defeat\nthe wage and hours bill.\"\nMORE WALL STREET\nREGULATION IS THREAT\nWASHINGTON. Nov. 21. (UP).\nChairman William O. Douglas of\nthe securities and exchange com\nmission. served notice on the\nhtock exchanges last night to al\nter their methods of operation be\nfore the commission is forced to\ndo it for them.\nCalling for a constitutional re\nvision of the exchange's adminis\ntrative and functional techniques.\nDouglas said that the traditional\nmethods operating as \"private\nmembership organizations\" which\nalways administered their affair,\n\"in much the same manner as pri\nvate clubs\"\u2014had become archaic\nl'or a business \"so vested in the\n(Continued on page four)\nAGED BREVARD\nWOMAN PASSES\nMrs. Trowbridge, One\nTime Educator, To Be\nBuried Thursday\nBREVARD. Nov. 24. (Special)\nMrs. Julia Goodhue Trowbridge,\nage 94. died here this morning at\n2:30 o'clock following an illness\nof ten days. Funeral services will\nbe held Thursday at .10::>0 a. m.\nat the Brevard Methodic church\nby Revs. J. H. Brandau. G. C.\nBinkman and Dr. T. F. Mart-. In\nterment will follow in Gillespie\ncemetery.\nMrs. Trowbridge is survived by\none daughter. Miss Alma Trow\nbridge, and four sons: Prof. C. H.\nTrowbridge, vice president of\nBrevard college; Roy (I. Trow\nbridge, Dubuque, la Rev. Leon\nard B. Trowbridge. Chicago, and\nProf. Arthur C. Trowbridge, Iowa\nCity.\nShe also leaves nine grandchil\ndren.\nMrs. Trowbridge was born in\nWestminster West, Vermont, and\nwas a graduate of Mount Holy\noke college, South Hadley, Mass..\nin the cla.\u00ab\u00abs of '8-1. Afterward she\ntaught there, and in other col\nleges in the east and in Nova Sco\ntia.\nShe had beon a resident of\nBrevard for the past quarter of\na ccntury, coming here from Chi\ncago. following the death of her\nlate husband. Dr. Samuel lloyt\nTrowbridge\nIndustrialist Shot\nhv Own Kill*1\nw\n\\v hen an associate went to his\nr\u00ab\u00bbom at S<a Island. Ua.. to discuss\na hunting t: i'.\u2022 with Howard K\nCotf!n. above, he found the 64\nycar-old industrialist killed by n\nnb\u00abt from the rifle he probably\nwould have used on the hunt.\nCoffin, a widower, was married\nai out six month< ago.\nCity BELLS TO\nOF SEAL SALE\nAnnual Drive, Funding\nMilk Station, Will Open\non Thanksgiving\nThe riiijrint: of all bell* in the\ncity tomorrow morning at 9:^0\no'cluck will usb\u00abT in the aunvd\nChristmas Seal Salt in Uendeivon\nville.\nConducted annually by the Wo\nman's club, the seal vale will open\non Thanksgiving and continue un\ntil Christmsa. The proceeds will\nbe used in the financing of the\nfree milk stations in city schools.\nThe milk stations supply one\nbottle of milk each day to under\nGREErtLfclGS\nnourished chil\ndren. and the\nneed this year\nis jrreator than\never before in\nthe history of\nthe operation\nof the milk sta*\nt.'.to, Mr (ieorge Wing. general\nchairman, said today. Tht> pro\ncoeds from the seal sale is the\nonly means of financ:ng the milk\nstations.\nMost people are entirely fa\nmiliar with the double crossed\nChristmas seais. Th -y have been\nsold here for many years by the\nclub women in co-operation with\nthe North Carolina Tuberculosis\nassociation. One-fourth of the pro\nceeds go to the state association\nand three-fourths remain here for\nlocal use.\nMr.-. Win;: is again serving as\ngeneral chairman of the ?ulc. She\noriginated the plan here more than\n10 years ago. The Junior Welfare\nclub will again have charge of the\nbooth in the postoffice. The Music\n(Continued on page three)\nTHANKSGIVING\nFOR BUSINESS\nFour Churches Plan Serv\nices; Drcij Stores Close\nFrom 1 to 5 P. M.\nERSKJNE'S FRESHMEN\nPLAY R1DG5ANS HERE\nA full holiday for merchants\nand business houses special\nsomces in thi\" city churches will\nmark the observance of Thanks*\njfix ini\u00bb- uay in lleudeibonville.\nCity and county offices, the\nState Trust company. postoffice, I\ncity librarv and other business\nhouses will observe a full holi- I\nday, and city drug stores will be\nclosed from I to 5 p. in.\nSpecial services are planned\nduring the day l'or most of the\ncity's churches.\nThe afternoon will find the j\nKid;.e Hilltoppcrs meeting the\nKrskine l'reshman football team\nin a Thanksgiving game nt the\nhigh M.huol athletic field at 2:30\np. m.\nA special sunrise service will be\nheld at 7:10 o'clock at the First\nBaptist church and the sermon will\nhe delivered by the Kev. D. W.\nThojnason of Kogefield, S. C. An\noffering will be tnkon for the\nMills home ar.d Kennedy home.\nThe Presbyterian church will\nhave a special service nt 1\u00bb a. m.,\nwith a special Thanksgiving mes\nigv by the Rev. L. T. Wildif, pas\ntor, and an offering for the\nMountain orphanage supported\nby the local Presbytery. The\nmusic will be appropriate to the\noccasion.\nA special service will be held at\nSt. James Episcopal church at\nIt):'**) o'clock with a sermon by\nthe pastor, Kev. James P. Burke.\nAn offering will be taken for the\nThompson home, at Charlotte.\nGrace Lutheran church will\nhave a special service at 10 a. m.\nwith a sermon by the Kev. A. W.\nl.ippard, pastor, and offering for\nthe Lutheran home at Salem, Ya.\nNo special service will be held\nat the First Methodist church due\nto the absence of the pastor, Rev.\n(I. R. Combs.\nHalf Way Mark Is Well\nPassed, Look for Com\npletion Soon\nStill short of their goal, but\nwell above the halfway mark in\nthe campaign. Chamber of Com\nmerce workers in the annual mem\nbership drive went hack to work\ntoday, and confidence was ex\npressed that the goal of approxi\nmately KOO memberships would\nbe attained.\nA number of concerns have not\nreported, and several of these are\nexpected to subscribe to a good\nnumber of memberships.\nThis morning the number of\nmemberships received it) the drive\nstood at 39\u00bb, approximately two\nthirds of the required number.\nParis Hears England Embarrassed Bv\nw\nHitler's Plan For Changed Diolomacv\nw 1 J\nGerman Program Calls for Recognition of Legal Rights\nto Possess Colonies, and Rejoining League\nPAR'S, Nov. 24. (UP)\nChancellor Adolf Hitler outlined\na seven-point program to Vis\ncount Halifax, including forma!\nrecognition of Germany's local\nright to possess colonics, it was\nreported in diploma'!** circles to\nday. Viscount Halifax, British\ncabinet .member visited Germany\nlast week.\nBritish Foreign Seercttary An\nthony Edon informed French Am\nbassador Andre Corbin of 'he\nHalifax-Hitler discussions, it was\nrumored. The program included\nthe following, according to these\nreports:\n1. Formal recognition of Ger\nmany's legal right to colonics.\n2. Upon recognition of this\nright by foreign powers, Hitler\nwoul dforego a practical realiza\ntion of his colonial ambitions for\na period of years, which he sub\nsequently set at six in his Aug*\nburtr speech.\n3. Franco and England to guar\nantee not to interfere in Austria,\nregardless of the nature of Gcr\nmanys' relations with Austria,\nwhile Germany guarantees nut to\nemploy force.\n4. The same stipulations in re\ngard to Czechoslovakia.\n5. Germany, Italy, France and\nEngland to form a fourpower\ngroup for consultation on all im\nportant international questions,\nthus resurrecting Premier Musso\nlini's long cherished dream of a\nvirtual fourpower directorate for*\nEurope.\nAnglo-French-American eco\nnomic cooperation to avoid at\n\u2022ackin-v the Keich's Auarchic re\ngime.\n7. Germany to return to the\nLeague of Nations after fulfill\nment of all previous conditions\n(Continued on page three)\n\"Pretending\" No More, They Seek\nThrone of France\nOn the heels of Switzerland':-- ous\nter of hi-* son, -Ik-in i, Count <le\nParis, r;;rht. because of a secret\nmeeting with French Rijfhti ts at\nGeneva, the Duke de Guise, above,\npretender to the non-existent\nthrone of Franco, announced his\ndecision to \"reconquer the throne\nof my fathers.\" Supporters de\nnied he contemplated military ac\ntion.\nFrench Minister Says Dictatorship\nWas To Pave Way For Monarchy\nUNTIL MONDAY\n$500 Judgment Is Granted\nTuesday in Highway\nAccident Case\nThe November term uf Hender\nson county superior court will un\njoin n this afternoon over the\nThanksgiving week-end ami w\nreconvene on next Monday morn\n'\"In court yesterday, Mrs. .trie\nM Woods was granted a jttng\nincnt of $500 in a damage action\nrrainst George Freeman. lht\nplaintiff was seeking damages of\n#2.000 as a result injuries al\nlegedly sustained in a\nnear Fletcher on Aug. -0. 19\u00ab\u2122.\nwhen an automobile in which she\nwas riding, and driven by Mrs\nBertha Jarretl. was m\nwith a truck belonging to 'he d\nlendant and driven by M. J. Ia>\n!01Ii, the case, the defendant con\ntended that the truck was forced\nto swerve into the car when a man\nstarted across the road in the path\nof the vehicle and that it va.\nnecessary to swerve in order to\navoid sti iking the man.\nThe court toduv was branny\nthe ease of William M. Oliver\nagainst C. L. and L. K.\ndoinif business a. th*? blue Ividgi\nSpecialty Printers.\nJurors for the second week ot\nthe court are: W. P\u00bb. Crcasman,\nJ. M. Ileal. V. C. Waters. G. D.\nk'.dlcv I K. Osteen. Delno .Me\nCall, Sam D. Rhodes. L. B. Whit\nal.er, Dewey Ca:je, W B. \u2022V,Jn l1uV'\nW R. Johnston, Wiley Rhodes,\nTect Pittillo, D. K. Pvessley. War\nren Waddell, R. C. Wilson, J. k.\nNelson, and J. I.. Maybin.\nCoffin Funeral\nIs Held Today At\nSea Island Home\nMen Hi*h in Manufacture\nand Finance Pay Tri\nbute; Death Unsolved\nSEA ISLAND. Ga., Nov. 24.\u2014\n(UP)\u2014Men hijeh in American\nmanufacturing and financial eli\ndes were gathered here today to\nruv their respects to Howard\nEarlc Coffin, famed industrialist\nand personal friend of two presi\ndents. n\nMany of them served as l>al'\nbearers at Coffin's funeral, held\nthis morning at 11 o clock from\nthe home of Alfred W. Jones, the\nindustrialist's cousin and in whose\nhome Coffin was stopping.\nCoffin's friends believed his\ndeath Sunday from a rifle ?hot\ninto his head was accidental.\n(Continued on page three)\nStales \"Conspiracy\" Pro\ngrain to Restore Rule\nDefunct 67 Years\nPARIS, Nov. 21. (l'P)\u2014Minis\nter <>f Inferior Marx Dormoy an\nnounced If*nirht that a \"con\nspiracy\" had been uncovered by\nwhich \"hooded men\" il.es Cagou\nlaid) terrorists plotted to over\nthrow the Popular Front govern\nment 1\u00bbv revolution, and restore\nthe monarchy that was driven\nfrom t!i\u00ab' throne \u00ab\u00bb7 years ago.\n\"Seized documents reveal that\nthe plotters aimed at substituting\na dictatorship for the republic be\nfore proceeding with a restoration\nof the monarchy,\" I)ornmy said.\nPormoy's announcement, made\nto newspaper correspondents sum\nmoned to the ministry of interior\nat 1<\u00bb p. m.< directly involved the\nexiled Puke of Guise, 63-year-old\nrcti nder to the throne who Mon\nday issued a manifesto announc\ning his decision to \"reconquer the\nthrone of my fathers.\"\nThe \"hooded men\" conspirators,\nDormoy said, had established a\n\"para military organization\"\nthroughout France and plotted to\nlaunch in uprising again it gov\nernment ministries.\nSecret police, running down\nlinks between I.es Cairoulardsand\na band <>f alleged German spies,\nmeanwhile raided the chateau of\ntin bue Francois Co'y, multi-mil\nlionaire perfumer, a*i<J discovered\na virtual fortress.\n\"A veritable plot against our\nKcpuMican institutions has been\nuncovered,\" Dormov raid.\n\"Investigations of the Surete\nNationale and the prefecture of\npolice revealed large amount of\n((Continued on page three.)\nFalls to 11 Above Zero\nTuesday After Brief Re\nlief During Day\nThe temperature dropped again\nlast night after the city and coun\nty yesterday had some relief from\nthe freezing temperatures of the\npast several days, and the low for\nlast night was 11 degrees, only\none degree above the low for the\nprevious night.\nThe temperature fell rapidly\nfrom p. ni. yesterday, when the\nreading was .'U degrees, and rose\nlapidly this morning, standing\nwell above freezing at noon.\"\nI.ow temperatures for the past\nfot r nights were respectively as\nfollows: 11, 10, I r\u00bb and 11 de\ngrees. Yesterdays' figures were as\nfollows:\nMaximum, 50 degrees; mini\nmum, 10 degrees; mean, .'JO de\nglees; day's range, 1U degrees.\nNormal mean temperature for\nNovember, 46.1 degrees; rainfall\nto date, .81 inch; normal Novem\nber rainfall, 3.11 inches.\nCHINESE FOOD\nRIOTS STAGED\nAT SHANGHAI\nJapanese Bomb Canton,\nSouth Chinese Sea\nport Today\nARE MAKING OVER\nTHE CHINESE MAP\nCANTON, China. Nov. :M.\u2014\n(l.'P).\u2014Japanese planes dropped\nbombs on this teeming South\nChinese sen port today. Fx tent of\ndamage was not learned imme\ndiately.\nChinese anti-aircraft guns fired\nat tlu- planes which first flew\nover the city at 10:50 a. m.\nSHANGHAI, Nov. 21. (IT).\u2014\nChinese refugees, many at the\npoint <>f starvation, rioted today\nin the French concession after\nthey heard rumors of new stores\nof rice had been landed. Many\nwere injured in the demonstra\ntions before the rice shops. Three\nrefugees were found starved to\ndeath.\nJAPANESE ASSUME\nSHANGHAI CONTROL\nCopyright, 1937, United Pre*\u00bb\nSHANGHAI. Nov. 21. (UP).\u2014\nThe Japanese today assumed al\nmost complete control of Shang\nhai after it was officially an\nnounced that the Chinese city\ngovernment, the garrison com\nmanders, the martial law head\nquarters and the Kuomintang or\nNational party headquarters were\nsuspending their functions. Only\nChinese courts in the internation\nal settlement and French conces\nsion were to continue.\nThe Japanese moved to elimi\nnate all Chinese activity even re\nmotely conected with the Nan\nking government by bringing\npressure to bear on the Shanghai\nmunicipal council, eliminating\npro-Chinese newspapers, taking\nover the customs service and\nwarning that they reserved the\nright to move into the interna\ntional areas to suppress any anti\nJapanese activity.\nAmerican Japanese Chinese\ndiscussions for establishment of a\nneutral zone in Nanking continu\ned. The Japanese consulate here\nreferred the request for such a\nzone from the civilian committee\nof Nanking to Japanese military\nand naval authorities. The pro\nposal suggested that the neutral\nzone include the Japanese, Ital\nian and L\\ S. embassies. A Japa\nnese embassy member said that\nthe Japanese were inclined to ac\ncept it. \"if it proves practicable.\"\nWhile Chinese continued fall\ning back before the steady Japa\nnese advance toward Nanking,\nJapanese authorities appeared to\nbe pushing forward their care\nfully-prepared plans to make\nover vast areas of China on a\npro-Japanese pattern.\nThe Kwuntung army in North\nChina was reported moving for\nward. without awaiting general\nsettlement of the North China\nand Vangtse valley problems, with\nits plans to consolidate the terri\ntory conquered into a manage\nable unit. Monday's formation of\na new Mongol federation with a\njoint council in Kalgan appeared\n(Continued on page three.)\nHOUSE GROUP\nFINISHES FIS\nFARM BILL\nSenator Copeland Says\nSenate Measure Not\nRepresentative\nFIND SENATE BILL\nHARD TO EXPLAIN\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 21. (UP)\nSenator Royal S. Copeland today\npresented charges t\u00ab> the senate\nthat farmers who approved the\nadministration's crop control bill\nwere not representative of the\nnation's agriculturist.*. Meantime,\ntlx- house agriculture committee\ntoday completed its permanent\nfarm hill, based on soil conserva\ntion.\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 21. (IT)\nRepublicans and Democrats open\ned a cross-fire of criitcism against\nthe senate's \"crazy-quilt\" crop\ncontrol bill yesterday, threatening\nplans of harassed administration\nleaders to speed passage of the\nmeasure which is No. 1 on Presi\nde lit Roosevelt's legislative pro\ngram.\nIrked by eight days of filibus\ntering and bickering in both\nhouses, senate leaders pressed the\nhodge-podge bill to floor debate\nami .Majority Leader AI ben W.\nBarkley, I>., Ky\u201e predicted pass\nage within a week despite obstruc\ntionist tactics by opponents.\nS*> great wus the hurry that\nthe leadership did not await a for\nmal report from the senate agri\nculture committee explaining the\nbill. This will be ready today.\nMeantime the senate spent an af\nternoon of Oratory on the neces\nsity of ai<ling the farmer but\nmade no spline recommendations.\nWhen perplexed senators asked\nfor details of the bill Chairman\nKllison I). Smith, I).. S. C., of the\nagriculture committee, replied that\nit was a \"middle of the road\"\nmeasure, that some phases of it\neven puzzled him, and that neither\nhe, nor his committ :c, knew how\nmuch it would cost. The commit\ntee Tuesday tightened penalty tax\nprovisions for cotton grown above\nacreage allotments to hit at buy\ners \"knowingly\" making purchases\nabove the limitation program.\nProtesting against \"this confus\ning and confounding\" situation,\nSenate Minority Ixuder Charles\nL. McNary, R., Ore., in an un\nusual maneuver, forced the clerk\nto read the entire senate bill. All\nbut 10 senators left the chamber,\nand the remainder dozed or wrote\nletters.\nAt one stage of the discussion,\nSen. Arthur H. Vandenberg, R.,\nMich., demanded to know how\nmuch the bill would cost the gov\nernment. Smith answered with a\nremark that \"efforts to aid agri\nculture should not be limited.\"\n\"It is a noble sentiment but a\nsenator cannot act intelligently\nwhen he does not know what he\nis authorizing,\" Vandenberg per\nsisted.\n\"It's a sort of sliding scale,\"\n\"Cotton Kd\" explained.\n\"Well, which way does it slide?\"\nVandenberg queried.\n\"Doesn't the senator see that\nyou cannot tell now?\" Smith said.\n\"No. I cannot see,\" Vandenberg\nreplied.\nSen. Tom Connally, D., Texas,\naccused Vandenberg of \"political\n(Continued on page four)\nGovernment Is Cautiously Probing\nAlleged Drive To Banish CIO Heads\nCharges Made Bridges and Pritchett Communists;\nOne Case Snarled in Two Departments\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24. (UP)\nThe federal government is cau\ntiously investigating an alleged\ncampaign to bring about the de\nportation of two Committer for\nIndustrial Organization officials\non the grounds that they arc aliens\nand member* of the Communist\nparty, it was learned last night.\nThe drive reportedly is being\ndirected against Harry Bridges,\nlongshoremen leader and Pacific\ncoast director of the C. I. 0., anil\nHarold Pritchett, president of the\nnew International Woodworkers\nunion.\nThe investigation Is being con\nducted. it was understood, to avoid\npossible charges\u2014in the event of\ndeportation that the government\nwas discriminating against organ\nized labor or any particular labor\nfaction.\nBridges, who is an Australian\nbut has taken out first citizenship\npapers, emphatically denied at a\nrecent private labor department\nhearing in New York that he is a\ncommunist. Pritchett also is rc-|\nported to have disclaimed any con\nnection with the party. Ho i* a\nCanadian and is in the United\nStates on a visitor's permit which\nhas been extended three times,\nthe last so that he could attend\nthe Woodworkers' convention at\nPortland, Ore., on Dec. 3.\nThe ease against Bridges is said\nto be supported by Gov. Charles\nII. Martin of Oregon, who bad his\nown investigators inquire into\nBridges' past and who supplied his\nown witnesses at secret labor de\npartment hearings on the coast.\nSolicitor Gerald Reilly of the la\nbor department personally had\ncharge of the investigation.\nIn addition to Martin's alleged\nopposition, rank-and-file members!\n(Contiuued from page four)\nMELEE FORCED\nON ST. LOUIS\nMOTOR PLANT\nOfficial Says U.A.W. Spon\nsored Affair no Strike;\nHints \"Invasion\"\nC.I.O. ORGANIZER IS\nAMONG ARRESTS\nST. LOl'IS. Nov. 21. (UP)~\nThe Ford Motor Company a<-en>.\nhly plant here was on an opcrat\nin*r basis after non-striking om\nployes battered through picket\nlines to take their places on the\nassembly line which started mo\\\ning on schedule.\nPlant Manager M. NT. Johnson\nsaid that there were f\u00bbK0 worker;\nin the plant which is \"norma\ntime of year.\"\nNine hundred are on the pay\nroll of the plant but all do not.\nwork at the same time because of\nseasonal requirements.\nJohnson said, \"Thi< is no\nIt may be an invasion but it is no\nstrike.\"\nNon-strikers broke the picket\nline composed of United Automo\nbile Workers' sympathizers from\nother unions. They broke tin lin\nby entering in automobiles and in\nsome cases passing a barrage ot\nrocks and stones.\nThe picket line was formed\nshortly past midnight and it wa\nestimated that several hut\nwere in it.\nTwenty-five policemen were ov\npatrol and when the line wa? bro\nken a number of arresti\nmade, anions' them Norman Smith,\nC. I. 0. organiser, who had beet\nreported beaten at Mei\nTenn., recently in an anti-union\ndemonstration.\nOne policeman was injured \"in\nthe ankle. Several fights broke out.\nThe strike had been called last\nnight by Delmond Garst. regional\ndirector of the V. A. W.\nGUARD MOVES W. P. A\nWORKERS TO FIELDS\nHA TON ROUGH, La.. Nov. JI\n(UP)\u2014Gov. Richard Leche i\nnight ordered the Louisiana n\u00ab\ntional guard to transport an \u00bb\\\u00abti\nmated 5,000 negro WPA wo\nhastily recruited from pr\nover the state, into the Sngaf\nBowl district to save S6.000.00fi\nworth of cane from cold weather\nLeche, ill with influenza, ca'led\na conference at the mansion and\nordered WPA work suspended. H\u00bb\ntelephoned the mayors of New Or\nleans, New Iberia, Alexandria.\nPlaquemine, Houma. Thibodnux,\nand Lafayette to cooperate, and\nordered Adj.-Gen. Rav Filming to\nmobilize guardsmen with truck\nand emergency camp equipment.\nWOULD BLUDGEON WAGE.\nHOURS BILL TO VOTE\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 24. (t P)\n\u2014Worried congressional leadet\nfailed yesterday to break the\ndeadlock gripping the wage*.hours\nbill in the house rules committee\nand put on new pressure in an at\ntempt to bludgeon it onto th<*\nfloor for a final vote.\nLast nifrht a petition which\nwould rebuke the committee by\ndischarging it from further con\nsideration of the measure, wns\nonly 10 signatures short of the\nrequired 218\u2014a majority of the\nhouse\u2014to bring success to the\ndrastic move. Sixteen signatures\nwere added after Majority Leader\nSam Rayburn, D., Tex., appealed\nto Democrats from the floor to\ndrop their fight on the bill.\nThe plea brought Republican\ntaunts that the leadership was un\nable to control the preponderant\nDemocratic majority.\nOne of the happiest Christ\nmas supcretitions is that fol\nlowed in Italy, of scattering\ngrain for birds to insure good\nfortune for the coming year.\nOl?.Shopping \"P&qi\n\"till","height":"28056","width":"20610"}}
